<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-258-127  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 258 127.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Jan 9 1989 v8 n1 p84(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Desktop III RFP amended.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Danca, Richard A.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Air ForceMicrocomputersDefense ContractsRequest for ProposalsWorkstations.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Desktop III RFP AmendedandM;Air Force officials at the Standard Systems Center (SSC) headquarters atGunter Air Force Base near Montgomery, Ala., have continued to fine-tune theDesktop III request for proposals in two new amendments issued last month.andM;The amendments do not change the February 1989 due dates for responses to themicrocomputer RFP set by Amendment 1 [GCN, Dec. 19, 1988].andP;  Amendment 2 makesminor clarifications and administrative changes.andP;  It also adds two minorcontract line items: stands for both the basic and advanced workstations thatwill allow users to stand the computers on end.andM;Amendment 3 provides answers to 219 questions submitted by vendors.andP;  Inresponse to some of these questions, SSC officials issued clarifications andmade minor changes to the RFP.andP;  In the amendment, SSC officials said theywill respond to other vendor questions in a future amendment.andM;The Air Force expects military users to buy 7,500 of the 16-but basicworkstations and 162,500 of the 32-bit advanced workstations over thecontract's five-year period.andM;Award Date Not SetandM;SSC officials have not announced an expected award date.andP;  The amended RFPcontinues to list April 1989 as the first month of the contract year.andM;The original RFP was issued Nov. 7, 1988, and set a Dec. 7 deadline forsubmissions.andP;  Now two of the four standard sections of the proposal are dueFeb. 1 and the other two on Feb. 10.andM;The current microcomputer contract with Zenith Data Systems expires at theend of February.andO;</TEXT></DOC>